## The OpenMRS KPI and KRI Framework

---

### Vulnerability Management Metrics

**KPI-VM-1: Critical and High Patch SLA Compliance Rate**

*Definition:* Percentage of Critical and High severity vulnerabilities (Inspector, Dependency-Check, ZAP findings combined) remediated within the defined SLA — Critical: 7 days; High: 30 days — measured monthly.

*Formula:* (Vulnerabilities remediated within SLA ÷ Total Critical/High vulnerabilities identified) × 100

*Target:* ≥ 95% SLA compliance. Below 90% triggers escalation to Health IT Manager.

*Data source:* Inspector monthly scan reports, Dependency-Check reports, POA&M item status for vulnerability findings.

*Why this KPI matters:* SLA compliance rate is an effectiveness metric — it measures not just whether scans are running but whether findings from scans are being acted on within the required timeframe. A system with 100% scan completion but 70% SLA compliance has a functioning detection capability and a failing remediation capability.

*Trend interpretation:* A declining compliance rate over successive months signals either increasing vulnerability volume (more findings arriving than remediation capacity can absorb) or declining remediation prioritization (findings are being deprioritized). Either requires a different response — the first requires process optimization; the second requires leadership escalation.

---

**KRI-VM-1: High Vulnerability Aging Counter**

*Definition:* Number of High severity vulnerability findings open beyond the 30-day SLA at the end of each month.

*Target:* Zero. Any High finding beyond 30 days without a POA&M entry with compensating controls is a policy violation.

*Threshold:* Zero open High findings beyond SLA = Green. 1-2 open with documented compensating controls and POA&M entries = Yellow. 3+ open, or any open without POA&M entry = Red.

*Data source:* POA&M, Inspector reports.

*Why this KRI matters:* This is the early warning metric that detects security debt accumulation before it becomes a material risk. A system that consistently has 0-1 aged High findings is managing its vulnerability backlog. A system where the aged High count climbs to 5, 8, 10 over several months is accumulating unacceptable risk that the monthly SLA compliance rate may be masking (because the numerator includes some on-time remediations while the denominator grows).

---

### Access Control Metrics

**KPI-AC-1: Quarterly Access Review Completion and Accuracy Rate**

*Definition:* Two components measured quarterly:
- Completion rate: Was the quarterly access review completed within 10 business days of the ISSO providing the account report? (Target: 100%)
- Accuracy rate: What percentage of accounts reviewed required no correction after the review? (Target: >95%, with any accounts requiring correction tracked for root cause)

*Data source:* Quarterly access review certifications, account correction records.

*Why this KPI matters:* Completion rate is an implementation metric — the review happened. Accuracy rate is an effectiveness metric — the review produced an accurate access state. The M-004 finding (over-privileged role persisting for six weeks between reviews) shows what an access accuracy problem looks like. An access review that consistently produces 1-3 corrections per quarter suggests the underlying provisioning process has gaps; the review is catching them but not preventing them.

*Trend interpretation:* Increasing correction rate over time signals a deteriorating provisioning process — the quarterly review is functioning but the root cause of mis-provisioning is not being addressed. Stable 0 corrections per quarter could signal either excellent provisioning hygiene or an insufficiently rigorous review (the M-004 pattern where role accuracy is not being evaluated, just account continuation).

---

**KRI-AC-1: Privileged Account Dormancy Indicator**

*Definition:* Number of IT Administrator and ISSO accounts with no login activity in the prior 30 days at the time of each quarterly access review.

*Target:* Zero. A privileged account with 30 days of dormancy should be immediately reviewed — no legitimate operational reason exists for a privileged account to be unused for 30 days.

*Threshold:* Zero dormant privileged accounts = Green. Any dormant privileged account = immediate ISSO review and Health IT Manager notification.

*Why this KRI matters:* Dormant privileged accounts are a high-value attack surface. An attacker who obtains dormant credentials for a privileged account may be able to use them without triggering the authentication anomaly alerts that would fire for an active account suddenly showing unusual activity. The 30-day threshold for privileged accounts (versus the role-differentiated thresholds from Day 70 for clinical accounts) reflects the elevated risk level of privileged access.

---

### Incident Response Metrics

**KPI-IR-1: Mean Time to Contain (MTTC) for Tier 3 Incidents**

*Definition:* For each Tier 3 (Critical) incident, the time from incident detection (GuardDuty finding timestamp or equivalent) to the completion of the initial containment action (account disabled, instance isolated, or equivalent). Measured per incident; trended over time.

*Target:* ≤ 30 minutes for initial containment action from detection. This is the target from the IR playbook (Day 81) — the IT Administrator should be able to take containment action within 30 minutes of a detection alert.

*Data source:* GuardDuty/Security Hub finding timestamps, CloudTrail records of containment actions (account disable, security group modification), incident report documentation.

*Why this KPI matters:* MTTC measures the effectiveness of the detection-to-containment pipeline — not just whether the alert was sent, but whether a human received it and acted on it within the required timeframe. A system where GuardDuty generated a HIGH finding at 2am Saturday and the containment action occurred 6 hours later has a 6-hour MTTC — the detection worked, the response did not. This metric distinguishes detection capability from response capability.

*Note on data volume:* At MyClinic's scale, Tier 3 incidents may be rare — potentially zero in a given quarter. When incidents are rare, MTTC is measured during the tabletop exercise rather than from live incidents. The tabletop scenario's "time to first containment action" is recorded as a proxy MTTC that reflects the team's current response capability.

---

**KRI-IR-1: Days Since Last IR Tabletop Exercise**

*Definition:* Number of days since the most recent documented incident response tabletop exercise.

*Target:* ≤ 365 days (annual exercise requirement from POA&M item 004). At 300 days since last exercise, begin scheduling the next one. At 365 days, Red.

*Threshold:* 0-300 days = Green. 301-364 days = Yellow (schedule next exercise). 365+ days = Red (AO notification, POA&M item escalation).

*Why this KRI matters:* The tabletop exercise is the only mechanism that tests whether the incident response capability actually works. As time passes since the last exercise, the team's familiarity with the IRP and their confidence in the escalation paths degrades — especially as personnel change and the informal "who do I call" knowledge is not consistently maintained. This KRI is a leading indicator of incident response capability degradation that would otherwise be invisible until a real incident reveals it.

---

### Contingency Planning Metrics

**KPI-CP-1: Backup Success Rate and RTO Compliance**

*Definition:* Two components:
- Backup success rate: Percentage of scheduled backup jobs (automated RDS snapshots + weekly S3 export) that complete successfully each month. Target: 100%.
- RTO compliance: Was the quarterly restoration test completed within the 4-hour RTO target? Target: Yes, with actual time recorded for trend analysis.

*Data source:* AWS Backup job completion status, CloudWatch backup monitoring alerts, quarterly restoration test documentation.

*Trend interpretation for RTO:* The M-003 finding identified a trend — restoration time increasing from 2:47 to 3:47 over one quarter. This trend, tracked through the RTO compliance metric, provides the data that supports the optimization investment before the RTO is missed. Without the trend data, the deterioration is invisible until the first failed test.

---

**KRI-CP-1: RTO Margin Trend**

*Definition:* The difference between the quarterly restoration test completion time and the 4-hour RTO target, tracked over successive quarterly tests.

*Calculation:* RTO target (240 minutes) minus actual restoration time = RTO margin.

*Q1 value:* 240 - 227 = 13-minute margin (3:47 completion time).

*Target:* RTO margin ≥ 60 minutes. Below 60 minutes = Yellow (optimization required). Below 30 minutes = Red (AO notification, immediate optimization priority).

*Why this KRI matters:* A passing restoration test that is 13 minutes from failure is not the same as a passing test that has 90 minutes of margin. The KRI margin trend converts the binary pass/fail into a directional signal: is the system's recovery capability improving, stable, or degrading? The M-003 POA&M item exists because the trend analysis surfaced the degradation early enough to address it proactively.

---

### Security Awareness Training Metrics

**KPI-AT-1: Training Completion Rate and Currency**

*Definition:* Percentage of active OpenMRS users who have completed the required security awareness training within the past 12 months, measured quarterly.

*Target:* 100% compliance, with zero users in the 10-day remediation window at any quarterly review.

*Data source:* Training completion records, OpenMRS user account list from most recent quarterly access review.

*Trend interpretation:* The AT-2 gap from Day 55 (users in the overdue remediation window at the time of the HC3 briefing) shows what low training currency looks like operationally — not just a compliance gap but an actual increased susceptibility to the threat vector (phishing credential theft) that the HC3 briefing identified as elevated.

---

**KRI-AT-1: Phishing Simulation Click Rate**

*Definition:* If a phishing simulation program is implemented — percentage of staff who click a simulated phishing link in a quarterly simulation.

*Target:* Below 5% click rate. Above 10% triggers targeted retraining.

*Note on current state:* MyClinic does not currently run a formal phishing simulation program — this is a future program development item. Adding a simple phishing simulation (available through free or low-cost tools) would convert AT-2 training completion from an implementation metric into an effectiveness metric. Completing the training proves the training occurred; not clicking a simulated phishing link proves the training produced behavioral change.

*This is the metrics gap the KPI/KRI framework surfaces:* The current AT-2 metrics measure implementation (training completion rate). No effectiveness metric exists for security awareness. Adding a phishing simulation would close this gap — and connect directly to the HC3 briefing's credential theft threat vector.

