## The Dashboard Design — Avoiding Metric Theater

The metrics dashboard should answer one question clearly and honestly for each audience: is the security program moving in the right direction?

For the ISSO: a complete view of all KPIs and KRIs with trend arrows (improving, stable, degrading) and threshold indicators (green, yellow, red). The ISSO needs the full picture to manage the program.

For the Health IT Manager: a simplified view of the metrics that require their awareness or action. Not all 10 metrics — the 4 that directly involve their role (access review completion and accuracy, CP-2 condition status, training completion, RTO margin).

For the AO: a further simplified view — three to five headline metrics that tell the authorization story. Are critical vulnerabilities being patched on time? Is the access review running correctly? Is the RTO margin adequate? These three metrics, with trend data, give the AO the information they need to assess whether the authorization remains appropriate.

The dashboard should not be optimized to look green. A dashboard that is always green because metrics are designed to be easy to achieve, or because red indicators are suppressed before they reach senior audiences, is producing metric theater — the appearance of security performance without the substance. The phishing simulation example is the clearest illustration: if the training completion rate is 100% (Green) but no effectiveness metric exists, the dashboard shows green in security awareness while the actual phishing susceptibility rate is unknown. Adding the phishing simulation click rate might show Yellow or Red — but that honest signal is more valuable than a false Green.

