## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The KRI concept — early warning before threshold breach — is directly illustrated by the **2021 Florida water treatment facility incident**, where an attacker gained remote access to the facility's operational technology systems and attempted to increase sodium hydroxide (lye) levels in the water supply to dangerous levels. The intrusion was noticed by an operator who saw the cursor moving on screen.

The water treatment facility had monitoring systems. What it did not have was KRIs calibrated to the operational threat: no alert for remote access from unexpected geographic locations, no alert for attempts to modify treatment chemical levels beyond normal operational ranges, no threshold-based indicator that would have surfaced the intrusion before the operator happened to notice the cursor.

This is the KRI design principle: KRIs should be calibrated to the specific threats that the risk assessment identified as most likely and most impactful. For OpenMRS, the KRI-AC-1 privileged account dormancy indicator is calibrated to the specific threat (compromised dormant privileged credentials) identified as a high-value attack vector. The KRI-VM-1 High vulnerability aging counter is calibrated to the specific threat (unpatched vulnerabilities exploited before remediation) that drives most healthcare breach incidents.

Generic KRIs — "number of security incidents" — are less valuable than threat-specific KRIs because they measure outcomes rather than leading indicators. By the time "number of security incidents" shows Red, the incident has already occurred. KRIs that show Yellow at 30 days of vulnerability aging give the ISSO 30 days to remediate before the threshold becomes a breach.

